        "creation_date": 1393370940,
        "body": "<p>I think there are several problems with your code:<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>You should go until size/2. You're pop-ing twice in each\niteration. Then check if the length was odd and just add the last\nremaining element if so. <\/li>\n<li>I think that your code only reverses your stack.<\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>This is not tested but i think it should look something like this (also took the liberty to get rid of some useless variables - performance probably isnt an issue in this case).<\/p>\n\n<p>Make your method return a stack and use it like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>st = switchPairs(st);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And the method's body:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public Stack&lt;Integer&gt; switchPairs(Stack&lt;Integer&gt; st){\n        Stack&lt;Integer&gt; q = new Stack&lt;Integer&gt;();   \n        for(int i = 0; i &lt; st.size()-1; i++){        \n            q.push(st.elementAt(i+1));\n            q.push(st.elementAt(i++)));\n         }\n         if(st.size()%2==1){\n            q.push(st.pop());\n         }\n         return q;\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>To keep it void (usage taken from <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/1068786/869594\">Here<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>AtomicReference&lt;Stack&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; ref = new AtomicReference&lt;Stack&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;(st);\nswitchPairs(ref);\nst = ref.get();\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>And the method's body:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>public void switchPairs(AtomicReference&lt;Stack&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; ref){\n        Stack&lt;Integer&gt; q = new Stack&lt;Integer&gt;();   \n        for(int i = 0; i &lt; ref.get().size()-1; i++){        \n            q.push(ref.get().elementAt(i+1));\n            q.push(ref.get().elementAt(i++)));\n         }\n         if(ref.get().size()%2==1){\n            q.push(ref.get().pop());\n         }\n         ref.set(q);\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
